Cyclistic Bike Sharing Data Analysis

Google Data Analytics Capstone Project by Avaes Shah

Introduction

This project is part of the Google Data Analytics Certification. The project features a business problem faced by a fictitious company Cyclistic. The project details can be found here. The aim of this project is demonstrate knowledge and skills in data analytics to solve a business problem. This project will take you through the 6 phases of data analysis pipeline:

  • Phase 1 : Ask
  • Phase 2 : Prepare
  • Phase 3 : Process
  • Phase 4 : Analyse
  • Phase 5 : Share
  • Phase 6 : Act

Statement of Business Task

Cyclistic is a bike sharing company based in Chicago. The service is offered to two types of customers: subscribers known as annual members and casual riders.

The financial team have shown that annual members are more profitable than causal riders.

The marketing director wants to target a marketing campaign aimed at the causal riders to switch to an annual membership.

In order to convert casual riders to annual member riders, we need to study the bike usage patterns for both casual and member riders and identify where the two are similar. That will allow us to identify the segment of casual riders who use hire their bikes repeatedly as they would benefit most from the annual membership.

The results from this analysis will first be presented to the stakeholders for their approval, and based on the recommendations of this study the marketing team will design their campaign.

Business task: To draw insights from Cyclistics historical trip data to see how annual members and casual riders use bikes differently for the period between 1st Jan 2022 to 31st Dec 2022. The analysis findings will drive the direction and design of the marketing campaign moving forward. The question to be answered:

1.How do annual members and causal riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Deliverables:

  1. Statement of business task
  2. Documentation report of cleaning or manipulation of data (changelog)
  3. Analysis summary
  4. Suppporting visualisations and key findings
  5. Top 3 recommendations based on the analysis

Phase 2 : Prepare

The Dataset

The 2022 dataset has been provided in CSV format. They are in 12 separate zip files, one for each month of 2022. There is no encryption or passwords on these files or dataset. Each file contains Cyclistic trip data in CSV format.

Source provided for dataset: https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html

The Change Log

Any changes made to the original dataset will be recorded in the following change log file: cyclistic_change_log.txt

Dataset Storage

I have downloaded the 12 zip files to a folder: Cyslistic on my local computer hardrive. Subsquently I have uncompressed the 12 CSV files into the folder Cyclistic.

Data Integrity

Does the Dataset ROCCC ?

  • Reliable: The dataset appears to be first-party data and is computer generated by bike bookings and usage. The data is generated by Cyclistics own systems and is held on their own servers (internal data) Upon examination however I noticed that some of the start and end station names were missing. The datasets reliability will need to be assessed through a series of SQL queries in Google BigQuery. A report to follow.

  • Original: The data is original because it belongs to the company Cyclist and has not been purchased from a third-party. The data is computer generated by the bikes and stations and held and maintained on the Cyclistic s own data servers.

  • Comprehensive: The data is comprehensive but the customer data portion has been censored under data protection. The business task requires comparisions of various metrics, which will need to be calculated and/or derived from the original dataset. The financial data and customer demographic data is absent, other than that the current dataset will be sufficient to carry out the initial business task.

  • Current: Yes: The last trip data was uploaded in December 2022.

  • Cited: This data is cited as first-party data belonging to Cyclist and is not from a third party.

Data Licencing

The data belongs to Bikeshare and is publicly licenced as open-source:

Licence: Bikeshare hereby grants to you a non-exclusive, royalty-free, limited, perpetual license to access, reproduce, analyze, copy, modify, distribute in your product or service and use the Data for any lawful purpose (License).

Link to full licence: https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement

Data Bias

  • Sampling Bias The data is representative of 100% of the population (all customers using the bikes) and no sample has been taken which would eliminate sampling bias.
  • Confirmation/interpretation bias The data is automatically generated through the use of the bikes. The data, which includes the above metrics, do not have any human intervention when collecting the data, therefore human error would not come into play here.
  • Observer bias (experimenter/research bias) n/a here as this data is computer generated and logged straight into the system with no human intervention to my knowledge.

Data Ethics

The reliability of the data collection would fall upon the system recording the data. There would appear to be missing data in some fields of end_station_name/start_station as some cells have been left blank, however we will attempt to reconstruct the missing data referencing the existing data with the GPS coordinates of the missing observations. A full report to follow.

Privacy

The original dataset contained Cyclistic user personal and financial data, this has been removed to protect the privacy of the users under data privacy legislation. Their financial and home address has been removed to protect their privacy prior to the dataset being hosted on an opensource public licence. The redacted data will would have allowed us to see the customer demographic information, but the protection of the customers details takes priority under data protection laws. We still have the necessary information to answer the business task.

Ownership

Control and ownership remains with Cyclistic company. The licencing for the trip dataset is exclusively controlled and owned by them.

Transaction transparency / consent / currency

The customers of Cyclistic would have been provided a declaration stating how their data will be used. They would have had to read and agreed with this statement before using the bikes. All customers who use Cyclistic have agreed to this declaration. The user reserves the legal right to request their personal information at anytime from Cyclistic.

Openness

Cyclistic has made its trip data publicly available after the customer details have been removed.

Proposed tools

The data sets are quite large, July 2020 dataset having nearly 800,000 rows. The best tools to handle large datasets would be BigQuery Data Warehouse (SQL) for data pre-cleaning, integrity/credibility testing, validation and R Studio for the analysis & visualisation. Tableau will also be used to support the visualisation deliverables.

Data Credibility & Integrity Testing

Testing Plan

Here we will upload the 12 raw dataset files into BigQuery and perform tests in SQL to determine the integrity and credability of the dataset.

We will be testing the dataset for:

  • duplicates
  • errors
  • missing values
  • nulls
  • regular expression
  • data type inconsistencies
  • data range conformity
  • data accuracy
  • data completness

the validation and integrity testing will be carried out in BigQuery, which I shall refer to as the pre-cleaning. The cleaning process where manipulation of the data cannot be completed in BigQuery due to the restrictions on write processes under the free licence terms of use. Hence the exporting of the dataset to CSV where the dataset will be imported and cleaned using R Studio.

Phase 3 : Process

Cleaning Action Plan

These items listed will be referenced throughout the cleaning process as item 1, item 2 etc

  1. Upload dataset (cyclistic_trip_pre_clean_2022.csv) into a data frame

  2. Update the end station (Green St & Madison Ave*) GPS coordinates

  3. Clean datatset:

  • Fill missing end and start station names and ids using existing station data from the dataset with average GPS coordinates as reference
  • Remove any blank spaces from the end/start station names
  • Convert station names and ids to lowercase
  1. Create calculated and derived columns:
  • route [chr] - the route from the start station to the end station
  • start_time [chr] - this is the time component in hh:mm:ss format for the started_at datetime object
  • end_time [chr] - same as above but for the ended_at datetime object
  • trip_dur_min[integer] - trip length in minutes (ended_at - started_at)
  • trip_dur_sec[integer] - trip length in seconds (ended_at - started_at)
  • weekday [ordered factor] - the weekday of hire
  • month [ordered factor] - month of hire
  • year [int] - year of hire
  • date [chr] - start date of hire
  • stn_dist_km [number] - this is the distance (km) between the start and end station as the crow flies

Missing GPS Coordinates Update

The list of start stations and their averaged GPS coorindates cannot be used because the two start stations have the same average GPS coordinates rendering this list unreliable.

Example:

63rd & western ave - north corner Lat: 41.78000 Lng: -87.68000
63rd & western ave - south corner Lat: 41.78000 Lng: -87.68000

both have the same averaged GPS coordinates.

Missing Start/End Station Data Review

Are the missing station names and ids important to the analysis ?

The business question is to see how the two user types use Cyclistic Bikes differently in order to qualify a marketing campaign. Will the missing end/start station names affect our analysis ? In my View - no. The end/start station names are not important as we have their corresponding GPS coordinates. The GPS of the pick up and drop off points will give us the distance between the points which we can then use to analyse the average trip lengths for each user type (members and casual riders). The station names are not that important, however, if we needed a summary of the stations which get used the most by each user type, then we may have to compromise 15 % of the dataset with that regard. However, the statistical summary of the other metrics will paint an accurate picture of the usage patterns for the two user groups.

The missing start/end names and ids have been added to the changelog and flagged up for stakeholder review in the final report.

Action Plan Item 4 : Create calculated and derived columns

Here we produce the following columns to prepare the dataset for analysis:

  • route [string] - this is the route taken from the start station to the end station
  • start_time [difftime] - this is the time component in hh:mm:ss format for the started_at datetime object
  • end_time [difftime] - same as above but for the ended_at datetime object
  • trip_dur_min[minutes - integer] - time difference (ended_at - started_at)
  • weekday [ordered] - the weekday the bike was hired derived from the started_at variable
  • month [ordered] - the month in which the bike was hired derived from the started_at variable
  • year [ordered] - the year in which the bike was hired derived from the started_at variable
  • date [ordered] - the date when the bike was hired derived from the started_at variable
  • stn_dist_km [km - double] - this is the distance between the start and end station as the crow flies

We also need to make some changes to the column names to make them easier to understand when carrying out the analysis

rideable_type > bike_type
member_casual > user_type

Lastly, we shall introduce a station distance (or trip distance if you prefer) column: stn_dist_km, which will be the distance between the pick up and the drop off in kilometers. This metric can be useful in estimating the distances traveled which can give great insights into how the two groups (members and casual) use the bikes.

# the station distance is calculated in km using the "geosphere" package and Haversine method and is the 
# distance between the start and end station as "the crow flies". The GPS coordinates have been used to
# perform this calculation

#add calculated column : stn_dist_km 
# trip_df$stn_dist_km <- with(trip_df, (distm(c(start_lng, start_lat), c(end_lng, end_lat), fun = distHaversine)[,1] / 1000) ) # this did not work

trip_df <- trip_df %>% rowwise() %>%  mutate(stn_dist_km = distm(c(start_lng, start_lat), c(end_lng, end_lat), fun = distHaversine)[,1] / 1000)

Descriptive Analysis

Here we examine the various metrics for insights and see how member and casual riders use the cycles.

Ridership Analysis

What was the total ridership split between the two user types in 2022 ?

# Percentage ratio between membership and casual riders in 2022

trim_df %>% 
  group_by(user_type) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_users = n(),
            Percentage_Split = round(100 * n()/nrow(.)))
# A tibble: 2  3
  user_type number_of_users Percentage_Split
  <chr>               <int>            <dbl>
1 casual            2316808               41
2 member            3344951               59
# Pie charts in R a bit tricky, you need to create a bar chart then turn it around on it's y-axis
# to make it a pie chart

bar_plot <- trim_df %>%      
  group_by(user_type) %>% 
    summarise(number_of_users = n()) %>% 
      ggplot(aes(x="", y = number_of_users, fill=user_type))+
        geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") + # the rest of the code is to make the pie chart minimal and tidy
        labs(title = "Cyclistic Casual-Member Ridership Split",
             subtitle = "The total member-casual rider ratio in 2022",
              caption = "Figure 1") +
                geom_text(aes(label = number_of_users), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), color = "white") +
                theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
                      axis.title.x = element_blank(),
                      axis.text.y = element_blank(),
                      axis.title.y = element_blank(),
                      panel.background = element_rect(fill = 'white'),
                      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
                      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                      plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
                      plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")) +
                      scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")


# here we curl the bar plot in on itself to make a pie chart
pie <- bar_plot + coord_polar("y", start=0)
pie

# save chart as jpg
ggsave("fig_1_cas_mem_pie.jpg")

Ridership Analysis Summary

There is a higher number of hires over the weekend than across the weekdays for casual riders, with Sunday seeing almost the same number for both membership and casual riders. The membership riders have nearly twice the number of hires during the working weekdays than casual riders Wednesday and Thursday being particularly high. This suggests that membership riders may be using the bikes for commuting whereas casual users use the bikes for leisure.

Weekend ridership appeared balanced 15.19 % membership riders 14.66 % casual riders

Work week : Mon - Fri showed around 19% more member users than casual 44.41 % membership riders 25.73 % casual riders

Maximum number of hires Casual - 472,082 on Saturday (8% of total) Member - 532,154 on Thursday (9% of total)

Lowest number of hires Casual - 263,187 on Tuesday (5% of total) Member - 387,117 on Sunday (7% of total)

Commuter Trend Analysis Summary

The percentage of riders (both member and casual) that make the daily commute in 2022 is 26.66 % (1,509,621 riders).

The membership riders that commute make up 17.87 % (1,011,756) whereas the casual riders 8.79% (497,865) in 2022

We can view the hourly commuting ridership (Mon-Fri) on a graph

You can see from figure 5c that there two peaks in hiring for membership rides, namely 7-8 am and 4-6 pm, these can be interpreted as the commuting hours.

When compared to casual riders, they have a peak between 4-6pm which suggests that they may be hire bikes for their home commute.

This segment of casual riders use their bikes repeatedly, which makes them a good marketing candidate for converting over to member riders.

Bike Type Analysis Summary

Bike type preference from the total of 5,661,759 bike hires in 2022 were as follows:

  • 45.89 % Classic bikes (2,597,944)
  • 51.03 % Electric bike (2,888,957)
  • 3.09 % Docked bike (174,858)

There was a balanced ridership between classic and electric bikes, whereas docked bikes had the least of the three types.

2022 Bike Hire Preferences

Classic Bikes member 65.78 % 1,709,054
casual 34.22 % 888,890

Electric Bikes member 56.63 % 1,635,897
casual 43.37 % 1,253,060

Docked Bikes casual 100 % 174,858

Casual riders prefer electric bikes, followed by classic bikes and lastly docked bikes which only made 3% of the years total. Member riders has seen an almost balanced preference between classic and electric, leaning towards classic.

Analysis Summary

  • 29.9% were weekend hires, 15 % casual riders and 14.7 % member riders

  • 26.6 % of hires were for commuting*, 17.9 % are member riders and 8.79% are casual riders

  • On average, casual riders have 77% longer trips than member riders

  • There were 18 % more member riders than casual riders

  • Member users maintained a steady average trip duration throughout the year, whereas the casual riders had a higher trip duration during the summer months which then dropped from Jun to Dec by 50%. This suggests that casual riders use their bikes for leisure and members for commuting.

  • April to October had 82 % of total ridership : 46% member riders and 36 % casual riders

Phase 6 : Act

Conclusion

The aim of this study was to see how casual and membership riders use their bikes differently. The purpose was to see if it is feasible to design a marketing campaign to convert casual users to a annual membership subscription.

The data was analysed and the top three findings were:

  1. 26.6 % of hires were for commuting*, 17.9 % are member riders and 8.79% are casual riders

  2. 29.9% were weekend hires, 15 % casual riders and 14.7 % member riders, both follow almost the same usage pattern

  3. Casual users prefer electric bikes and weekend hires, they mainly use their bikes for leisure.

Action

If casual users were to convert over to membership, they would have to use the bikes regularly to reap the benefits of an annual membership subscription.

Based on the results of this study, we see that casual users who make the daily commute, that would be 8.79% of the total ridership, would benefit the most from the annual subscription as it would save them money. This is based on the assumption that casual users who hire out the bikes during commuting hours and days are using them for that purpose alone.

It is also shown that casual usage of bikes, mainly electric peak in summer months, where a weekend trip duration is longer than member riders. Casual riders who regularly make weekend trips would benefit from the annual membership plan, as it would save them money in the long run.

Conclusion

The segment of casual riders who:

  • make the daily commute
  • regular weekend leisure trips

would be best fit the market campaign to switch over to a monthly subscription, as it will save them money in the long run.

Further Analysis

The data does not show how frequently casual users use their bikes. To gain these insights we will need to analyse financial information which will tell us if any casual users have made repeated hires and over what period.
